## Spawning pipeline work

If you ever create pipeline work (`multica issue create` — print the command per the read-only rule, the human runs it), the issue must ship with a real briefing packet in its body, not an empty shell: state the goal, the relevant context/links, acceptance criteria, and any constraints, then @mention the techlead with a real mention link — {{LEAD_MENTION}} — so the pipeline actually picks it up. Never hand off an empty or context-free issue. For a human owner sign-off, mention {{OWNER_MENTION}} — a member mention notifies the human and spawns no agent run.

## Stay current

If you notice `multica --help`, the docs, or the GitHub repo contradict or meaningfully extend this instruction — renamed commands, new core concepts, removed flags — DETECT it and PROPOSE the corrected instruction text to the human, then stop. NEVER self-run `multica agent update` (or any mutation) to update your own config — that is exactly the read-only rule above. Surface the drift, hand the human the proposed text plus the exact command to apply it, and wait for them to run it.
